QUALIFICATION: American Journal of Conchology, 1(1): 19; Conrad originally included two species: Pleurotoma cristata Conrad, 1847, and Cochlespira engonata Conrad, 1865. The type designation of Cochlespira has been controversed [Palmer & Brann, 1966, Bulletins of American Paleontology, 48(218): 589]; however, although Cossmann was uncertain about the relationships of Cochlespira engonata, he clearly accepted it as type species. Later, after the establishment of Cochlespiropsis Casey, 1904, with C. engonata as type species, Cossmann [1906, Essais de paléoconchologie comparée, 7: 221] invalidly cited Pleurotoma cristata as type species of Cochlespira

Senior objective synonym of Pleurotoma
AUTHOR: Röding

QUALIFICATION: Mémoires de la Société d'Histoire Naturelle de Paris, 1: 73; Pleurotome [Link, 1807, Beschreibung der Naturalien-Sammlung der Universität zu Rostock: 118], Pleuroma [Rafinesque, 1815, Analyse de la Nature: 145], and Pleurotomina [Beck, 1847, Amtlicher Bericht über die 24. Versammlung Deutscher Naturforscher und Aerzte in Kiel, (1846): 115, 217] are incorrect subsequent spellings. See also Pleurotomus and Pleurotomites. Invalid: junior objective synonym of Turris, with the same type species

AUTHOR: Montfort

QUALIFICATION: Conchyliologie systématique, 2: 538; Invalid: junior homonym of Turris Röding, 1798 [Turridae]. Turris [Gray, 1857, Guide to the systematic distribution of Mollusca in the British Museum, 1: 23] is listed in Neave, 1940, Nomenclator Zoologicus, 4: 594, as a separate entry, but is apparently used in the sense of Montfort for miters and not turrids. See also Vulpecula and Turricula H. & A. Adams, 1853
